{{Infobox company | name = ARMZ Uranium Holding Co. | logo = Лого-АРМЗ.png | logo_size = 120px | caption = | type = | traded_as = | fate = | predecessor = | successor = | foundation = {{Start date|1992}} | founder = | defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | location_city = [[Moscow]] | location_country = Russia | locations = | area_served = | key_people = Vadim Zhivov (Chairman) | industry = [[Uranium mining]] | products = | services = | revenue = | operating_income = | net_income = | assets = | equity = | owner = | num_employees = | parent = [[Atomenergoprom]] | divisions = | subsid = | homepage = {{URL|www.armz.ru}} | footnotes = }} '''ARMZ Uranium Holding Co.''' (AtomRedMetZoloto, a contraction of a Russian phrase meaning "Atom Rare Metals Gold") is a Russian [[uranium mining]] company. It is wholly owned by [[Atomenergoprom]], a part of [[Rosatom]].<ref name=wnn141107> {{cite news | publisher= World Nuclear News | url = http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/newsarticle.aspx?id=14386 | title = Russian corporate fusion continues | date = 2007-11-14 | accessdate=2009-06-24}} </ref><ref name=wnn220408> {{cite news | publisher= World Nuclear News | url = http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/newsarticle.aspx?id=17378 | title = Russia signs up with Armenia, Namibia next | date = 2008-04-22 | accessdate=2009-06-24}} </ref>
AtomRedMetZoloto was founded in 1992. In 2008, all uranium mines in Russia as well as uranium mining related assets in other countries owned by Rosatom subsidiaries were brought under ARMZ Uranium Holding Co.
ARMZ Uranium Holding Co. mines uranium in Russia and Kazakhstan. New operations involve Armenia, Namibia and Canada.<ref name=wnn220408/><ref name=wnn220708>{{cite news |publisher = World Nuclear News |url = http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/newsarticle.aspx?id=19034 |title = ARMZ links with Areva, plans new U plant |date = 2008-07-22 |accessdate = 2009-06-24 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090704170418/http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/newsarticle.aspx?id=19034 |archive-date = 2009-07-04 |dead-url = yes |df = }}</ref> In June 2009, ARMZ Uranium Holding Co. acquired 16.6% of shares in the Canadian uranium mining company [[Uranium One]] in exchange for a 50% interest in the [[Karatau, Kazakhstan]] uranium mining project, a joint venture with [[Kazatomprom]].<ref name=wnn150609>{{cite news |publisher = World Nuclear News |url = http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/newsarticle.aspx?id=25418&terms=ARMZ+ |title = Kazakh tie-in for Uranium One and ARMZ |date = 2009-06-15 |accessdate = 2009-06-24 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090704165158/http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/newsarticle.aspx?id=25418&terms=ARMZ+ |archive-date = 2009-07-04 |dead-url = yes |df = }}</ref> In December 2013 an internal reorganization of Rosatom extinguished the interest of ARMZ, making Uranium One a direct subsidiary of Rosatom.<ref name = WISE >[http://www.wise-uranium.org/ucscr.html WISE Uranium Project] "Following the completion of the Going Private Transaction, and an internal reorganization by ARMZ's parent corporation, Russia's State Atomic Energy Company 'Rosatom' in December 2013, Uranium One is now a wholly-owned indirect subsidiary of Rosatom and is no longer controlled by ARMZ." updated April 1, 2015, accessed April 23, 2015</ref>
In December 2010, ARMZ agreed to buy Australian-based [[Mantra Resources]] for US$1.15 billion, including its stake in a Tanzanian mine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mining-journal.com/finance/armz-makes-a$1.16bn-offer-for-mantra|accessdate=2010-12-17|title=Mining Journal - ARMZ makes A$1.16bn offer for Mantra|date=2010-12-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930192637/http://www.mining-journal.com/finance/armz-makes-a$1.16bn-offer-for-mantra|archive-date=2011-09-30|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>
