{{Expert-subject|Chemistry|documentation|talk=Tag added as no citations to speak of|reason=lack of any substantial referenced chemical content|date=May 2014}}
Fuel surrogates are mixtures of one or more simple fuels that are designed to emulate either the physical properties ([[vapor pressure]]) or combustion properties ([[laminar flame speed]], [[heating value]], etc.) of a more complex fuel.  While surrogate mixtures can demonstrate more than one characteristic of the desired fuel, more often than not different components are required in order to emulate the wide variety of properties that are of interest to researchers.{{cn|date=May 2014}}  [[Jet fuel]] is an example of a fuel requiring a surrogate for experimental research and numerical modelling due to its complexity and high content variability from one batch to the next.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Eddings|first=E.G.|author2=Sarofim, A.F.|title=Formulation of a surrogate for the simulation of jet fuel pool fires|journal=Comb. Sci. Tech.|volume=177|pages=715–739|year=2005|doi=10.1080/00102200590917248}}</ref>{{primary source-inline|date=May 2014}} Neat hydrocarbon jet fuel surrogate components include [[decane]], [[dodecane]], [[methylcyclohexane]], and [[toluene]].{{cn|date=May 2014}} Gasoline surrogate components include [[n-heptane]] and [[iso-octane]].{{cn|date=May 2014}} [[Hexadecane]] is a diesel surrogate component.{{cn|date=May 2014}} Biodiesel surrogate components include [[methyl butyrate]] and methyl decanoate.{{cn|date=May 2014}}

