{{Infobox power station | name = Ndugutu Hydroelectric Power Station | name_official = | image = | image_size = | image_caption = | image_alt = | location_map = Uganda | location_map_size = | location_map_caption= Location of Ndugutu Power Station | coordinates ={{coord|00|36|56|N|29|58|46|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | relief = no | country = [[Uganda]] | location = Ndugutu, [[Bundibugyo District]] | status = P | construction_began = 2017 | commissioned = 2018 Expected | decommissioned = | cost = | owner = KMR East Africa Company | operator = | ps_units_operational = | ps_units_manu_model = | ps_units_uc = | ps_units_planned = | ps_units_cancelled = | ps_units_decommissioned= | thermal_capacity = | ps_electrical_capacity = {{convert|4.8|MW|abbr=on}} | ps_electrical_cap_fac = | ps_annual_generation = | website = | extra = }}
'''Ndugutu Hydroelectric Power Station''', also '''Ndugutu Power Station''', is a proposed {{convert|4.8|MW|abbr=on}} mini-hydropower station in the [[Western Region, Uganda|Western Region]] of [[Uganda]].<ref name="Emu">{{cite web|url=http://www.era.or.ug/index.php/2013-10-23-18-03-21/2013-10-23-18-12-48/latest-news/479-application-for-a-license-for-the-establishment-of-a-4-8mw-hydro-power-plant-in-bundibugyo-district | title=Application for a License for the Establishment of a 4.8MW Hydro Power Plant in Bundibugyo District |accessdate=22 December 2017 |location=Kampala |date=28 October 2015 |publisher=[[Electricity Regulatory Authority]] (ERA)| author=ERA}}</ref><ref name="Bbiri">{{cite web|accessdate=22 December 2017 | url=https://www3.opic.gov/Environment/EIA/Sindila/Initial_Project_Summary_KMRI_Sindila_SHPP_final.pdf | title=Sindila Mini-Hydropower Station: Initial Project Summary |date= |author=OPIC |publisher=[[Overseas Private Investment Corporation]] (OPIC) | location=Washington, DC |format=PDF}}</ref>
==Location== The power station would be located on the ''Ndugutu River'', just outside [[Rwenzori National Park]], in [[Bundibugyo District]], in Uganda's Western Region, approximately {{convert|20|km|0}}, by road, southwest of the town of [[Bundibugyo]], the nearest urban center and the location of the district headquarters.<ref>{{cite web|date=22 December 2017 |last=Globefeed.com | url=https://distancecalculator.globefeed.com/Uganda_Distance_Result.asp?fromplace=Bundibugyo%2C%20Western%20Region%2C%20Uganda&toplace=Kakuka%2C%20Western%20Region%2C%20Uganda&dt1=ChIJeYUekghkYRcRdGX-v0A2tJw&dt2=ChIJufOJmfl5YRcRGqbds3IqJps | title=Distance between Bundibugyo, Western Region, Uganda and Kakuka, Western Region, Uganda | accessdate=22 December 2017|publisher=Glbefeed.com}}</ref> This location is in close proximity of the {{convert|5.25|MW|0}} [[Sindila Hydroelectric Power Station]], which is owned by the same developer.<ref name="Bbiri"/>
==Overview== Ndugutu HEPS is a [[run-of-river]] mini-hydro power plant whose planned maximum installed capacity is 4.8 MW.<ref name="Ssatu">{{cite web| url=http://www.getfit-reports.com/2016/projects/ndugutu/ | location=Kampala | title=GetFit Uganda: 2016 Annual Report: Ndugutu Hydroelectric Power Station | publisher=GeFit Uganda Reports |author=GetFit Uganda}}</ref> The project is owned by KMR East Africa Company<ref name="Bbiri"/> (also Ndugutu Power Company Uganda Limited),<ref name="Emu"/> the project developers. The construction of this power station was budgeted at US$15 million, with US$3.2 million in GetFit concessions.<ref name="Ssatu"/>
==Timetable== The project received approval for GetFit support in June 2015. Financial close was reached in 2016. Construction was expected to start during 2017, with completion expected during the fourth quarter of 2018.<ref name="Ssatu"/>
