{{Infobox power station | name = West Durham Wind Farm | image = Moorland and a wind turbine farm from Hedley Hall Lane, Tow Law - geograph.org.uk - 1409488.jpg | image_caption = West Durham Wind Farm | location_map = County Durham | coordinates = {{coord|54.7680|-1.8216|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | name_official = | country = [[England]], [[United Kingdom]] | location = near [[Tow Law]], [[County Durham]] | status = Operational | construction_began = | commissioned = May 2009 | decommissioned = | cost = | owner = [[ESB Group]] | operator = | ps_units_operational = 26 × 2 MW | ps_units_manu_model = [[REpower Systems|REpower]]: MM82 | wind_hub_height = | wind_rotor_diameter = | wind_rated_speed = | wind_farm_type = | wind_site_elevation = | wind_site_usage = | wind_offshore_depth = | wind_offshore_distance = | ps_electrical_capacity = 24&nbsp;MW | ps_electrical_cap_fac = | website = }}
'''West Durham Wind Farm''' is a [[wind farm]] near [[Tow Law]], [[County Durham]], [[England]].
==History== Developed by County Durham-based company the [[Banks Group]], the farm was planned as the largest wind farm in [[North East England]]. Construction of the farm began on the 11 July 2008. It was hoped that the commissioning of the turbines would make County Durham the first English county to hit its 2010 renewable energies target.<ref name=so_far>{{cite web |url = http://www.journallive.co.uk/north-east-news/todays-news/2008/07/11/holy-war-over-wind-farm-near-st-andrew-s-church-61634-21323098/ |title = BIGGEST SO FAR |first = Ben |last = Guy |date = 11 July 2008 |work = The Journal |accessdate = 10 August 2011 }}</ref> The farm was commissioned in May 2009. In 2009 it was purchased by the [[Electricity Supply Board]]<ref>http://www.edie.net/news/news_story.asp?id=16796</ref>
==Design and specification== The wind farm has a [[Intermittent energy source#Terminology|nameplate capacity]] of 24[[Megawatt|MW]], containing twelve Repower MM82 [[Wind turbine|turbines]] each rated at 2MW.<ref>http://www.bwea.com/ukwed/operational.asp</ref> It was the first wind farm containing turbines supported on driven steel tubular piles.<ref>http://www.grontmij.co.uk/environment/geotech/Pages/westdurham.aspx</ref>
